## Controller decision logic (routing rules — NOT LLM guessing)

```
If alert entity = pod / node / deployment / namespace
  → Infra path directly (no graph lookup needed)

If alert entity = service / job / DAG name
  → Inventory lookup first → resolve runtime → pick worker

If alert entity = collection / table / topic / queue
  → Dataflow graph first → resolve owning service → Inventory → pick worker

If entity is unclear
  → Fallback: observability labels, log tags, metric labels, past incidents
```

**Routing formula: LLM extracts entities → rules decide worker → worker runs**
LLM is NOT used to choose which tool to call or which cluster to query.

---

## Context loading — staged and budgeted

### Stage 1 (always, cheap)
- Alert payload
- Matched inventory record
- 1-hop graph neighborhood
- Recent deploy/config change
- Basic health status

### Stage 2 (only if Stage 1 is inconclusive)
- Targeted logs (service + time range, max N lines)
- Targeted metrics (related KPIs only, last 15–30 min)
- DAG run status
- Kafka consumer lag
- DB error rates

### Stage 3 (only if still unclear)
- Code snippets (relevant service/module only — not full repo)
- Configs
- Runbooks/Confluence pages
- Distributed traces
- Past incident history

**Hard limits per investigation:**
- Max workers called: configurable ceiling
- Max tool calls per stage: defined per worker
- Max tokens per stage: enforced
- Stop early if confidence threshold is met

---

## Worker output contract (what every worker must return)

```json
{
  "checked": ["what was inspected"],
  "findings": ["what was found"],
  "evidence_refs": ["log line IDs, metric timestamps, etc."],
  "ruled_out": ["what was eliminated"],
  "confidence": 0.0,
  "next_suggested_check": "optional — what controller should look at next"
}
```

Workers return compact structured output only. No raw log dumps passed between workers.

