## Known loopholes and guardrails

| Risk | Guardrail |
|---|---|
| Stale/wrong inventory | Version in Git, validate on update, fallback to labels |
| LLM-driven routing | Rules-first, LLM only for entity extraction and summaries |
| Over-investigation | Max hop limit, stop-on-high-confidence policy |
| Token bloat | Stage-gated retrieval, compact worker output contracts |
| Wrong conclusion from partial evidence | Require evidence chain before RCA, not loudest symptom |
| Ambiguous multi-owner collections | Primary owner field + producer/consumer priority rules |
| Unsafe remediation | Hard approval gate, read-only default, separate Executor worker |
| Outdated Confluence | Treat as support context only — structured metadata takes priority |

---

## Scale considerations

- Airflow DAGs at volume
- Mongo collections at volume
- Multiple K8s clusters (EKS)
- Kafka topics spanning multiple services

**Do not manually maintain a full dependency graph.**
Use hybrid model:
- Thin manual inventory for routing (service → runtime, cluster, owner, repo)
- Auto-derived graph from DAG code + app code + configs
- RAG/retrieval layer over code and docs for deep understanding
- Controller routes on metadata; workers pull code only when needed

---

## What is NOT locked yet (decide later)

- Exact framework (LangGraph, custom, etc.)
- Model vendors
- How memory/incident history is stored
- Whether workers are graph nodes, services, or MCP servers
- Whether Executor is centralized or per-domain
- Approval UX (chat, ticket, dashboard)
- How aggressive auto-remediation is in lower environments

---

## One-line principle

> Inventory tells the controller HOW to debug.
> Dataflow tells the controller WHERE to start.
> Workers do the reasoning. Controller does the routing.
> Evidence first. Conclusion second. Approval before action.
